Airbnbs in New York City

Introduction

Airbnb is a platform in which people may be able to provide or obtain temporary lodging in homes that are not occupied at that time. This is relatively novel compared to the more conventional hotels that travelers would try to obtain lodging in. How people would perceive this industry and how their personal preference when choosing between the lodgings provided, however, is a concept that is not very familiar to us. In order to gain more insight into this issue, we looked into the Airbnbs in New York City, as this is a very popular traveling destination, to see if we can find some sort of association between personal preferences and the types of lodging or promotion that is provided of the lodging.

In this project, we mainly wanted to find the answer to which different factors that influence peoples choice of lodging. By looking at how the Airbnb owners would characterize their lodging, the price of the housing, and the trend of how people characterize the Airbnbs that are recently opened, we found that people staying in New York preferred quiet lodgings, lodgings that are cheap, and are becoming more interested in the areas that they are located. The answer to our questions were supported with the fact that most people has stayed in quiet lodgings, those lodgings are relatively cheap, people chose to live in less expensive places when choosing lodgings, and that most newly opened Airbnbs included their location within their name.

Background:

The data used within this analysis contains information about the different listings provided on Airbnb. Those information ranges from the way the owners named their lodgings to the location or type of lodging provided. A more detailed description of the information provided will be shown below.

The different pieces of information are organized into columns, described as below. There are 16 variables within the dataset.

  1. Listing ID: The unique identification number of each Airbnb represented in New York. Represented in the dataset as id.

  2. Name: This is the name of Airbnb in New York. Represented in the dataset as name.

  3. Host ID: The owner/host of the Airbnb has his/her own unique identification number. This is helpful to classify different Airbnb that are owned by a single host. Represented in the dataset as host_id.

  4. Host Name: This is the name of the host/owner of the Airbnb. Represented in the dataset as host_name.

  5. Neighbourhood Group: This includes the five major locations within New York City: Bronx, Brooklyn, Manhattan, Queens and Staten Island where the Airbnb is located Represented in the dataset as neighbourhood_group.

  6. Neighbourhood: These are the different areas within the five major neighbourhoods in New York City where the Airbnb is located. Represented in the dataset as neighbourhood.

  7. Latitude: This is the latitude of the Airbnb in New York Represented in the dataset as latitude.

  8. Longitude: This is the longitude of the Airbnb in New York. Represented in the dataset as longitude.

  9. Room Type: This tells about the Airbnb space type. Represented in the dataset as room_type.

  10. Price: This is the price in dollars of living in the Airbnb for a single night. Represented in the dataset as price.

  11. Minimum Nights: This is the minimum night the individual has to stay at the Airbnb. Represented in the dataset as minimum_nights.

  12. Number of Reviews: This is the number of reviews the Airbnb has received. Represented in the dataset as number_of_reviews.

  13. Last Reviewed: This includes the last date the Airbnb was reviewed. Represented in the dataset as last_review.

  14. Reviews per month: This includes the mean number of reviews the Airbnb receives in a month. Represented in the dataset as reviews_per_month.

  15. Host Count: This tells us about the number of Airbnbs owned per host. Represented in the dataset as calculated_host_listings_count.

  16. Availability: This tells us about the number of days when Airbnb is available for booking. Represented in the dataset as availability_365.

Dataset

We got our dataset from Kaggle, which is an open source website used by many people for the purpose of data analysis. The URL link to our dataset is: https://www.kaggle.com/dgomonov/new-york-city-airbnb-open-data

Unusual factor to be aware of:

The data does not provide information on how many people have actually booked the lodging. The only data to reflect the number of people who had stayed there is the number of reviews it has received.

Background Information on questions posed:

To know what consumers consider when choosing between lodgings when choosing which Airbnbs to reside in, we tried to find which kind of Airbnbs travelers choose the most. In the data, we made some assumption to be able to obtain the data needed to answer our big question.

Assumptions made about the data:

  1. We assume that the reviews can only be given by the individuals that have stayed in those Airbnbs. Since Airbnb would encourage people to give reviews after each stay, the number of reviews is directly proportional to the number of people that have stayed at that Airbnb.

  2. We think that the airbnbs that have an extended period of availability, but have no reviews, or any latest review date would suggest that it is newly opened.

With the assumptions we made above, we went on to figure out the factors that influence the travelers decisions, and then we went on to look at how the owners of Airbnbs have adjusted their advertising strategy in reflection of the newly adjusted preferences of the consumers.

Inferences:

In New York City, people prefer to stay in quiet Airbnbs. We think this may be because people value this characteristic in face of the loud and fast-paced nature of the city.

However, there may be other factors that make the Airbnbs mentioning this sort of characteristics to be so attractive to the consumers. Therefore, we started looking at different factors of Airbnbs that may affect the way that may influence a persons decision as to where to stay.

Since airbnbs with characteristic words of quiet are reviewed the most , it would be interesting to see how their prices compares to the prices of other airbnbs in New York City.

As we can see from the above graph, the mean price of the Airbnbs that are characterized as quiet are on the lower end on the price, being the characteristic with the third cheapest price. We would suspect the reason for this is related to the location and the type of rooms that these Airbnb offer. It is reasonable to assume that quiet Airbnbs would usually provide cheaper room types and tend to be located at cheaper locations. Whether or not they are due to inherent nature or due to choice of owners of these Airbnbs would need further test to be known clearly. However, the hypotheses of possibilities are still able to be formed from analysis.

To confirm our inference, we tried to find the relationship between type of room and the Airbnbs that mentions the characteristic quiet in their name first. In the data set we have three room types: Entire homes or apartments, Private rooms, and Shared rooms. Since the price of Airbnbs with the characteristic words of quiet are on the lower end we would expect that these Airbnbs would offer more rooms than homes or apartments.

Do owners of Airbnbs who have characteristics words of quiet in the names offer more of specific room type?

What we see from the graph is that Airbnbs with quiet characteristics offers more private rooms rather than any other type. This makes sense as quiet rooms generally afford more privacy and relatively smaller size of room compared to apartments would both result in the low price of quiet rooms.

Another aspect of the graph is that airbnbs with characteristic words of quiet in their names hardly have Airbnbs with shared rooms even though shared rooms should cost less. This would make sense as shard rooms, albeit cheaper, would mitigate the peace and quiet of the traveler residing in the room. This is further evidence supporting our claim that quiet Airbnbs offer more private rooms than the other types of rooms.

After looking at the room type, we turn to analyze our guess of the second reason for these rooms to be so cheap, being that they would be located at cheaper neighbourhoods within New York City.

Does the location relates, if at all, with the price of the airbnb?

As seen in the graph, we can conclude that the airbnbs in New York that are located in Manhattan as significanly more expensive than the airbnbs present elsewhere.The neighbourhood apart from manhattan have nearly the same mean price. This seems to suggest that locations in New York would effect the price, with the price of being located in Manhattan having major impact on the price of the lodging.

In order to prove whether the the mean price of the airtbnbs in Manhattan is statistically different from the mean price of any other boroughs, we first used the Analysis of Variance test(ANOVA).

Analysis of Variance Test

Analysis of variance is a collection of statistical models and their associated estimation procedures used to analyze the differences among group means in a sample. In this case, we wanted test if the mean price of the different locaitons in New York are different.

The null hypothesis here is that the mean price of airbnbs in each borough is the same.

The alternative hypothesis is that the mean price of the airbnbs in each borough is different.


airbnb_anova = airbnb_1 %>% 
  group_by(neighbourhood_group) %>% 
  summarize(n = n())

fit = aov(price ~ neighbourhood_group, data = airbnb_anova)
print(anova(fit))

By testing these hypotheses using analysis of variance, we found that the p-value is 2.2e-16 which is less than the significance level of 0.05, so we can reject the null hypothesis in favour of the alternative hypothesis. This means that we can conclude that there are statistical significant differences between the mean prices of airbnbs in different boroughs of New York.

Next, we used 4 individual t tests to compare the mean price of the airbnbs in Manhattan with the mean price of airbnbs in different boroughs.

T-Tests

The algorithm used in t-tests is to compare the two means to see if the difference between the two is statistically significant. Since we are trying to compare the mean price of Airbnbs in different boroughs of New York City, this type of testing seems to be very fitting.


t_test = function(mean1, sd1, total1, mean2, sd2, total2)
{
  z = (mean1 - mean2) / sqrt((sd1*sd1 / total1) + (sd2*sd2 / total2))
  if (total1 > total2) {
    df = total2 - 1
  }
  else { df = total1 - 1 }
  
  p_val = pt(z, df)
  return (p_val)
}

First t-test:

Comparing the mean price of airbnbs in Manhattan to the mean price of airbnbs in Brooklyn.

The null hypothesis here is that the mean price of the airbnbs in Manhattan is the same as the mean price of the airbnbs in Brooklyn.

The alternative hypothesis is that the mean price of the airbnbs in Manhattan is not the same as the mean price of the airbnbs in Brooklyn.


manhattan_air = airbnb_1 %>% 
  filter(neighbourhood_group == "Manhattan") %>% 
  mutate(mean = as.numeric(mean(price)),
         sd = sd(price),
         total = NROW(price)) 

manhattan_air = manhattan_air %>% 
  select(mean, sd, total) %>% 
  distinct()

brooklyn_air = airbnb_1 %>% 
  filter(neighbourhood_group == "Brooklyn") %>% 
  mutate(mean = as.numeric(mean(price)),
         sd = sd(price),
         total = NROW(price))  %>% 
  select(mean, sd, total) %>% 
  distinct()
  
(t_test(brooklyn_air$mean, brooklyn_air$sd, brooklyn_air$total,
       manhattan_air$mean, manhattan_air$sd, manhattan_air$total))

Second t-test:

Comparing the mean price of airbnbs in Manhattan to the mean price of airbnbs in Queens.

The null hypothesis here is that the mean price of the airbnbs in Manhattan is the same as the mean price of the airbnbs in Queens.

The alternative hypothesis is that the mean price of the airbnbs in Manhattan is not the same as the mean price of the airbnbs in Queens.


queens_air = airbnb_1 %>%
  filter(neighbourhood_group == "Queens") %>% 
  mutate(mean = as.numeric(mean(price)),
         sd = sd(price),
         total = NROW(price)) %>% 
  select(mean, sd, total) %>% 
  distinct()

(t_test(queens_air$mean, queens_air$sd, queens_air$total,
       manhattan_air$mean, manhattan_air$sd, manhattan_air$total))

Third t-test:

Comparing the mean price of airbnbs in Manhattan to the mean price of airbnbs in Bronx.

The null hypothesis here is that the mean price of the airbnbs in Manhattan is the same as the mean price of the airbnbs in Bronx.

The alternative hypothesis is that the mean price of the airbnbs in Manhattan is not the same as the mean price of the airbnbs in Bronx.


bronx_air = airbnb_1 %>%
  filter(neighbourhood_group == "Bronx") %>% 
  mutate(mean = as.numeric(mean(price)),
         sd = sd(price),
         total = NROW(price)) %>% 
  select(mean, sd, total) %>% 
  distinct()

(t_test(bronx_air$mean, bronx_air$sd, bronx_air$total,
       manhattan_air$mean, manhattan_air$sd, manhattan_air$total))

Fourth t-test:

Comparing the mean price of airbnbs in Manhattan to the mean price of airbnbs in Staten Island.

The null hypothesis here is that the mean price of the airbnbs in Manhattan is the same as the mean price of the airbnbs in Staten Island.

The alternative hypothesis is that the mean price of the airbnbs in Manhattan is not the same as the mean price of the airbnbs in Staten Island.


staten_air = airbnb_1 %>% 
  filter(neighbourhood_group == "Staten Island") %>% 
  mutate(mean = as.numeric(mean(price)),
         sd = sd(price),
         total = NROW(price)) %>% 
  select(mean, sd, total) %>% 
  distinct()

(t_test(staten_air$mean, staten_air$sd, staten_air$total,
       manhattan_air$mean, manhattan_air$sd, manhattan_air$total))
Findings from the first t-test:

The p-value we got from performing such test is 8.243e-200, which is almost 0. We have strong evidence against the null hypothesis and in favor of the alternative hypothesis.

Findings from the second t-test:

The p-value here was 1.15e-215, which is almost 0, also strong evidence against the null hypothesis and in favor of the alternative hypothesis.

Findings from the third t-test:

The p-value here was 7.124e-137, which is almost 0, also strong evidence against the null hypothesis and in favor of the alternative hypothesis.

Findings from the fourth t-test:

The p-value here was 1.56e-8, which is almost 0, also strong evidence against the null hypothesis and in favor of the alternative hypothesis.

Conclusions from the series of t-test:

We can conclude from the series of t-tests that Manhattan has different mean price than any other borough in New York City, which was seen from the p-values in each case which was usually in the hundreds of negative power of the scientific notation. Furthermore, from the graph displaying the mean price of all the boroughs in New York City, we saw that Manhattan had a higher price than any other place in New York City. Hence, we can say with statistical proof that the airbnbs in Manhattan have a higher mean price than airbnbs in different boroughs in New York City.

Part II

From Part I, we can conclude that Manhattan certainly has a higher price than all the other places within New York City. Since this location sticks out so much, we decided to do a bit more digging into it. In particular, we wanted to know the relation between the price that people are willing to pay and the location that these Airbnbs are at.

So we are analyzing the extent to which people feel its worth it to spend high amounts of money on expensive Airbnbs. For this question we will be targeting the individuals that are wealthy and the closest way to predict that in our case is to just focus our attention on the Airbnbs in Manhattan. The reason behind this is that as we found out previously Manhattan has the significantly higher prices for Airbnbs so the individuals who choose to live in Manhattan need to be affluent.

What are the most expensive locations in the Manhattan?

From the graph above, we found out that Tribeca is the neighborhood in Manhattan that has significantly higher average price of airbnbs followed by the Battery Park City.

What are the average number of reviews these neighbourhoods in Manhattan receive? This would give us the idea of the number of people visiting the airbnbs in that region

From the graph, we can see that the Airbnbs in Tribeca and Battery Park City received the lowest amount of reviews. To be exact Tribeca was fifth lowest and Battery Park City was second lowest. This indicates that the higher prices of these Airbnbs are associated with lower amount of people willing to stay there. This might mean that they are not worth the price. Another thing to point out is that Airbnbs in East Harlem, are on the lower end of the average price but the Airbnbs in East Harlem have the highest mean number of reviews. So we can conclude that not many people choose to stay in the more expensive Airbnbs. Although we have drawn the conclusion that people who chose to stay in Manhattan should affluent, they still chose not to live in the locations with high prices. This may be due to the fact that affluent people may choose to stay in hotels. Since there is possibility that people who chose to stay in Airbnbs tend to not possess that much income, such as students, so even the slightly affluent ones would still need to watch their expenditures and therefore would not chose to live in higher priced Airbnbs. So the areas being worthy of investing much money may not be very well represented with Airbnb datasets. However, just viewing the users of Airbnb, the higher priced Airbnbs were not considered to be worth the price.

PART III

To know more about the types of Airbnbs owners would be willing to provide, we wanted to know the status quo, so we conducted analysis that looks into the newly opened Airbnbs within New York City. Since it is more possible to believe that people will open new Airbnbs if there is reason to believe that the market in that region is profitable and are in demand, we believe that looking into the new Airbnbs opened would provide us not only with insight as to the kind of Airbnbs that owners like to provide, but also further show the preferences of the people choosing lodgings.

Asumption made with this question : We think that the airbnbs that are very available, but have no reviews, or any latest review date would suggest that it is newly opened. This is because there is reason to believe that if a new Airbnb is opened for most of the year, the likelihood of having not one single customer to leave review is highly unlikely. So we think they should be newly opened as that would provide the explanation that people were not able to provide reviews yet.

The condition we used to filter out all the observations that could potentially be new airbnbs are that these airbnbs have no reviews per month, they have no last review date and their availability throughout the year is more than hundred days.

Discussion

We looked at the characteristics, locations, and prices of the Airbnbs provided and how that would affect a persons choice in choosing the Airbnbs to stay in.

From our findings above, we found that people generally like to stay in quiet rooms in New York City, which are mostly located in Brooklyn. People who stay in Airbnbs do not enjoy splurging on overly expensive places to stay in, and prefers affordable places instead. And that recent interest in location has shifted to Manhattan, with much more lodging being provided and people willing to go there.

From these findings, we can draw a general profile of the group that seeks Airbnb accommodations to be frugal and prefers privacy and calm surroundings. We can also draw a general profile of the group that provides Airbnb accommodations to be cunning business people who provide accommodation according to the consumers preferences.

Potential short-coming of the analysis arise from two parts, one is that the information we gathered is based on the number of reviews that these Airbnbs have received. However since we are not able to know the quality of these reviews, how genuine these reviews are, or even whether or not these reviews are positive, it is very hard for us to conclude the actual preference of people with Airbnbs. This is also a problem when we were trying to evaluate the newly opened Airbnbs the base of our analysis was based on an assumption we made of the types of Airbnbs that resemble newly opened ones. In order to resolve this issue, we could go on the web in search for datasets that contains more of the information needed, as in the positive or negative reviews or number of people staying the Airbnb or the number of new Airbnbs that opened, to add to our original dataset in order to improve the accuracy of our inferences.

Another shortcoming of our analysis is the lack of statistical tests to test the accuracy of our inferences. However due to the magnitude of our analysis and our lack of time, we were not able to attribute much time into those. If given more time, we should design statistical tests to test the accuracy of our claims, such as how strong the correlation between low price and the characteristically quiet Airbnbs are in certain regions.

So in general, we found that the price, location, and characteristics of the accommodation are all factors that influence peoples choice of lodging. People are able to choose accommodations that fit their preference, and that owners of Airbnbs would work to meet these preferences. So Airbnb is indeed a platform that is very efficient, and brings much benefit to the people who use it. We believe that this is a study worth going deeper in if given time, as knowing the preferences of people would help owners make better decisions when providing accomodation so that there would be more optimal choices provided for people seeking a place to stay.
